      <h2>What You Need to Know About NDA Translation</h2>

      <h3>The Real Question: Will This Protect Me in UAE Courts?</h3>
      <p>An NDA is only as strong as its weakest clause. If you need to enforce confidentiality in the UAE, the Arabic translation is what judges will read. A poorly translated NDA can leave your trade secrets exposed, even if the English version was drafted by top lawyers.</p>

      <p>Here is the reality: UAE courts enforce NDAs, but they interpret the Arabic version. If the Arabic translation uses vague terms where the English used precise ones, you lose protection. If the remedy clauses are softened in translation, your enforcement options shrink.</p>

      <h3>What Makes NDA Translation Different</h3>
      <p>Unlike other contracts, NDAs rely on carefully defined terms that must carry the same meaning throughout the document. Every time "Confidential Information" appears, it must refer to exactly the same scope. Key challenges include:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Defined terms consistency:</strong> "Confidential Information" must translate identically every time</li>
        <li><strong>Scope language:</strong> "Including but not limited to" has specific legal effect in Arabic</li>
        <li><strong>Exclusion precision:</strong> What is NOT confidential is equally important</li>
        <li><strong>Duration clarity:</strong> "Two years from termination" must be unambiguous</li>
        <li><strong>Remedy preservation:</strong> "Injunctive relief" must retain its strength</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Common NDA Scenarios in Dubai</h3>

      <div class="comparison-box">
