            <li>Employee confidentiality agreements</li>
            <li>Consultant NDAs</li>
            <li>Exit interview acknowledgments</li>
            <li>Non-compete with confidentiality</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>UAE Court Enforcement Reality</h3>
      <p>UAE courts have become more sophisticated in handling NDA disputes. Recent cases show that courts will:</p>

      <ul>
        <li>Examine the Arabic text closely for scope and duration</li>
        <li>Award damages when breach is proven and quantified</li>
        <li>Grant injunctions to prevent ongoing disclosure</li>
        <li>Consider the nature of the confidential information</li>
        <li>Evaluate whether reasonable protective measures were taken</li>
      </ul>

      <p>The key is having an Arabic version that supports your enforcement position. Weak translations lead to weak enforcement.</p>

      <h3>Bilateral vs Unilateral: Why It Matters for Translation</h3>
      <p>The structure of your NDA affects translation approach:</p>

      <div class="process-breakdown">
        <h4>Unilateral NDA</h4>
        <p>One party discloses, one party receives. The translation must clearly identify which party has obligations. Used for: employee onboarding, vendor relationships, initial business pitches.</p>

        <h4>Bilateral (Mutual) NDA</h4>
        <p>Both parties share and both have obligations. More complex translation because duties are reciprocal. Used for: partnerships, joint ventures, M&A discussions where both sides share sensitive data.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Industry-Specific Terminology</h3>
      <p>NDAs often include technical definitions specific to your industry:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Technology:</strong> Source code, algorithms, APIs, architecture diagrams</li>
        <li><strong>Healthcare:</strong> Patient data, clinical protocols, formulations</li>
        <li><strong>Finance:</strong> Trading strategies, client lists, deal terms</li>
        <li><strong>Manufacturing:</strong> Production processes, supplier networks, cost structures</li>
        <li><strong>Real estate:</strong> Investment models, tenant information, development plans</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Our translators identify industry-specific terms and ensure they have proper Arabic equivalents that courts will understand in context.</p>

      <h3>What Courts Look At</h3>
      <p>When an NDA dispute reaches UAE courts, judges examine:</p>

      <ul>
        <li>Was the information clearly defined as confidential?</li>
        <li>Did the disclosing party take reasonable protective measures?</li>
        <li>Was the breach intentional or negligent?</li>
        <li>What damages resulted from the disclosure?</li>
        <li>Is the requested remedy proportionate?</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Strong translation of the definition and remedy clauses directly supports your position on each of these points.</p>

      <h3>Common Translation Mistakes to Avoid</h3>

      <div class="mistake-list">
        <div class="mistake-item">
          <span class="mistake-icon">✗</span>
          <div>
            <strong>Generic confidentiality terms:</strong> Using vague Arabic words instead of legally precise terms
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="mistake-item">
          <span class="mistake-icon">✗</span>
          <div>
            <strong>Inconsistent defined terms:</strong> Translating "Confidential Information" differently each time
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="mistake-item">
          <span class="mistake-icon">✗</span>
          <div>
            <strong>Softened remedy language:</strong> Reducing "shall be entitled to injunctive relief" to weaker phrasing
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="mistake-item">
          <span class="mistake-icon">✗</span>
          <div>
            <strong>Ambiguous time periods:</strong> "Reasonable time" instead of specific durations
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Realistic Timeline</h3>
      <p>Standard NDAs (3-5 pages) complete in 6-12 hours. Complex NDAs with extensive schedules, annexes, or highly technical definitions may need 24 hours. If you have a deal closing or meeting deadline, tell us upfront. We prioritize based on your business needs.</p>

      <div class="info-callout">
        <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle"></i> Before Signing: Translation Review</h4>
        <p>If your counterparty is presenting an Arabic NDA for signature, have it reviewed before you sign. Understanding what you are agreeing to in the governing language is essential for informed consent and future enforcement.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
